sections.text:
Since real-world driving cannot guarantee consistent encountered situations for each driver, some drivers may lack the reaction data of some situations. Therefore, we attempted to complete the missing data using the k-Nearest Neighbour (k-NN) and the weighted average methods. This approach can also be considered k-NN regression. The k-NN method has been widely used in practice (Gallego et al., 2018;Samworth, 2012). The concept of the method is to classify the testing data based on the k-closest training data in the feature space. The reactions of the drivers were labelled using 3 classes, including a positive class (acceleration greater than 0.5 m/s 2 ), a moderate class (acceleration greater than -0.5 m/s 2 and less than 0.5 m/s 2 ) and a negative class (acceleration less than -0.5 m/s 2 ). In this paper, the training data include the driver's encountered time gap, the speed difference data, and the labels of their reactions. To calculate the distance between the missing situations and the collected data, the centre values of the grids shown in Fig. 1 are used to represent the possible situations. By applying the k-NN method (k=5 in this study), the k data with the smallest Euclidean distance to the missing situation are used to determine the label of the situation. The labelling approach reduces the influence of noise and errors which could significantly change the result of data completion. Then, the acceleration for each missing situation is calculated according to the weighted average method shown in equation (1). The acceleration values of neighbouring data points with the same label are considered and weighted by the inverse of their distance.

where A i is the approximate acceleration value of the missing data point i;

is the acceleration value of the j -th nearest neighbour data point with the same label as the missing data point i; and D ij represents the distance between the missing data point i and the training data point j.

